<p>For as long as humans have settled the coast, hurricanes have been a menace to civilization:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Within the last two or three years, people have begun to think that the islands and peninsulas along the Texas and Louisiana Coast are unsafe for human abiding places. And Galveston Island is but a waif of the ocean, liable at any moment of being engulfed and submerged by the self-same power that gave it form. – Braman’s Information About Texas, 1858</p>
</blockquote>

<h2>1900 Galveston Hurricane</h2>
<p>Surprisingly, with all the talk of the increasing risk caused by climate change, the deadliest storm in American history occured over a hundred years ago.</p>

<h3>Hurricane Naming</h3>
<p>Despite being the deadliest hurricane in American history, this storm is simply known by the location it struck. Meterologists did not decide to give official names were not given to hurricanes until 1953. Since then, names are recycled from six lists–each corresponding to different regions of the world. However, names associated with notoriously deadly or costly storms are removed.</p>


<h3>Path</h3>
<p>While meteorologists had eyes on the 1900 hurricane as early as August 30, they were unable to get a good idea of its trajectory. As shown on the map below, as it moved over the Gulf of Mexico over the Florida Keys, it rapidly strengthened and then took a sudden westward turn. Although ships in the area were able to get a fix on its trajectory, the limited communications abilities of the time prevented this information from reaching shore.</p>
<pre class="sql"><code>WITH galv1900 AS
(SELECT path_intensity FROM hurricane_summary 
WHERE season::int = 1900
AND st_intersects(path, (SELECT geom FROM us_states WHERE name LIKE 'Texas')))
SELECT *, saffir_simpson_color(wind_max_kt) as sshs_color
FROM json_to_recordset(array_to_json((SELECT * FROM galv1900)))
AS x(lon float, lat float, wind_max_kt float, time text, sshs text)</code></pre>

<h3>The Aftermath</h3>
<p>Before the storm, Galveston, Texas was a bustling coastal town. However, when it struck on September 8, 1900 the storm with its 140 mph winds and massive storm surge killed between 6000-12000 people (out of a population of 37000). This effectively ended the “Golden Era of Galveston”.</p>

</div>

<h2>Hurricane Tracking</h2>
<p>At least in the United States, it is unlikely that another 1900 Galveston could occur. Armed with a bevy of aircraft, radar, sallites, and computer models, today’s metereologists are much more able to accurately predict the path of a hurricane and warn those in harms way.</p>

<h3>Effectiveness</h3>
<p>The graph below speaks for itself in regards to the efficacy of modern hurricane tracking.</p>
<pre class="sql"><code>SELECT
  season, count(name), round(AVG(wind_max_kt)::numeric, 1),        
  saffir_simpson(AVG(wind_max_kt))
FROM hurricane_summary
WHERE season > 1900 AND wind_max_kt::int != -999
GROUP BY season
ORDER BY season</code></pre>

<h3>Motivation</h3>
<p>The Weather Bureau (now the National Weather Service) didn’t always have the blessing of adequate funding. However, Hurricanes Carol and Edna in 1954 reversed their fortunates, convincing Congress to allocate more funds for hurricane research.</p>
<pre class="sql"><code>SELECT *, saffir_simpson_color(wind_max_kt) as sshs_color
